<text top="390" left="515" width="11" height="8" font="font8" id="p1_t86" reading_order_no="97" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">( )<a href="">d [43</a>] that DIALIGN is more sensitive than</text>
<text top="87" left="55" width="495" height="7" font="font9" id="p1_t87" reading_order_no="2" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">Table 3: DIALIGN alignment scores for anchored and non-anchored alignment of five reference test sets from BAliBASE. As anchor</text>
<text top="96" left="55" width="493" height="7" font="font9" id="p1_t88" reading_order_no="3" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">points, we used the so-called core-blocks in BAliBASE, thereby enforcing biologically correct alignments of the input sequences. The</text>
<text top="106" left="55" width="499" height="7" font="font9" id="p1_t89" reading_order_no="4" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">figures in the first and second line refer to the sum of DIALIGN alignment scores of all protein families in the respective reference set.</text>
<text top="115" left="55" width="499" height="7" font="font9" id="p1_t90" reading_order_no="5" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">Line four contains the number of sequence sets where the anchoring improved the alignment score together with the total number of</text>
<text top="125" left="55" width="498" height="7" font="font9" id="p1_t91" reading_order_no="6" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">sequence sets in this reference set. Our test runs show that on these test data, biologically meaningful alignments do not have higher</text>
<text top="134" left="55" width="306" height="7" font="font9" id="p1_t92" reading_order_no="7" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">DIALIGN scores than alignments produced by the default version of our program.</text>
